    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading a manual for a cessna 172 and saw stuff about the pitot tube. can u explain how it actually works to measure airspeed? and why is it such a big deal if it gets blocked up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The pitot tube works by measuring the difference between the total pressure (stagnation point) and static pressure to calculate airspeed. If it gets blocked by ice or debris, the system loses the relative pressure differential, causing the airspeed indicator to quit or show incorrect \"stuck\" readings. This is a major safety risk because flying with lost airspeed awareness can lead to uncontrolled stalls and loss of control before the pilot even notices. Pilots are trained to recognize these symptoms immediately and perform an emergency \"cutoff\" to stop airflow through the system.",
