    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. what kind of stuff usually blocks them up though? like is it just ice usually or can other things get in there?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ice buildup is the most common cause, especially in cooler or humid weather clouds where moisture freezes around the probe. However, insects like mosquitoes or de-icing fluid in foggy conditions can also act as a dangerous abrasive or block the sensitive openings. Additionally, external debris such as bird droppings or small rocks from wind shear can physically obstruct the small air intake. Because these blockings can happen in split seconds without warning, pilots often check for frost or blockage before every takeoff to ensure safety.\n</think>\n\nIce buildup is the most common cause, especially in cooler or humid weather clouds where moisture freezes around the probe. However, insects like mosquitoes or de-icing fluid in foggy conditions can also act as a dangerous abrasive or block the sensitive openings. Additionally, external debris such as bird droppings or small rocks from wind shear can physically obstruct the small air intake. Because these blockings can happen in split seconds without warning, pilots often check for frost or blockage before every takeoff to ensure safety.",
